          "kind": "data",
          "title": "oligotypes",
          "artifactType": "CONCEPT",
          "description": "Oligotyping is a computational strategy that partitions a given set of sequences into homogeneous groups using only a subset of target nucleotide positions . Oligotyping was first described in 2011 and has primarily been applied to 16S ribosomal RNA gene amplicons to resolve closely related but distinct that differ as low as one nucleotide at the amplified region, exceeding the sensitivity of the popular strategy of the time, 97% OTU clustering. Other papers that demonstrate the strengths of this approach include the following: 1 , 2 , 3 , and 4 .",
